18.369 | Mathematical Methods in Nanophotonics | http://ocw.mit.edu/courses/mathematics/18-369-mathematical-methods-in-nanophotonics-spring-2008 | textbook:Readings listed below from 'Textbook' are from the required course text:  Joannopoulos, John D., Steven G. Johnson, Robert D. Meade, and Joshua N. Winn. Photonic Crystals: Molding the Flow of Light. Princeton, NJ: Princeton University Press, 2008. textbook:For a more sophisticated treatment of Hilbert spaces, adjoints, and other topics in functional analysis, a good text is:  Goldberg, Israel, Seymour Goldberg, and Marinus Kaashoek. Basic Classes of Linear Operators. Boston, MA: Birkhauser Verlag, 2004. level:Graduate instructors:Steven G. Johnson term:Spring 2008 features:Assignments (no solutions), Exams (no solutions) description:Find out what solid-state physics has brought to Electromagnetism in the last 20 years. This course surveys the physics and mathematics of nanophotonics&mdash;electromagnetic waves in media structured on the scale of the wavelength.Topics include computational methods combined with high-level algebraic techniques borrowed from solid-state quantum mechanics: linear algebra and eigensystems, group theory, Bloch's theorem and conservation laws, perturbation methods, and coupled-mode theories, to understand surprising optical phenomena from band gaps to slow light to nonlinear filters.Note: An earlier version of this course was published on OCW as 18.325 Topics in Applied Mathematics: Mathematical Methods in Nanophotonics, Fall 2005.
18.376J | Wave Propagation | http://ocw.mit.edu/courses/mechanical-engineering/2-062j-wave-propagation-fall-2006 | level:Graduate instructors:Chiang Mei,  Rodolfo Rosales,  Triantaphyllos Akylas term:Fall 2006 features:Lecture notes, Assignments (no solutions), Exams (no solutions), Images on Flickr description:This course discusses the Linearized theory of wave phenomena in applied mechanics. Examples are chosen from elasticity, acoustics, geophysics, hydrodynamics and other subjects. The topics include: basic concepts, one dimensional examples, characteristics, dispersion and group velocity, scattering, transmission and reflection, two dimensional reflection and refraction across an interface, mode conversion in elastic waves, diffraction and parabolic approximation, radiation from a line source, surface Rayleigh waves and Love waves in elastic media, waves on the sea surface and internal waves in a stratified fluid, waves in moving media, ship wave pattern, atmospheric lee waves behind an obstacle, and waves through a laminated media.
